is an irreducible character of $\Gamma$ and all the irreducible characters of $\Gamma$ are of this form. See \cite{ste} for details. It is well known that irreducible characters of a group form an orthonormal set. Hence the eigenvectors (in Theorem \ref{c2}) corresponding to irreduciable characters of $\Gamma$ are linearly independent. Therefore all the eigenvalues of $Cay(\Gamma, S)$ can be evaluated explicitly as
\begin{eqnarray}\label{1e}
\lambda_{i_1,\ldots,i_{k}}=\sum\limits_{(s_1,\ldots,s_{k})\in S}\omega_{n_1}^{i_1s_1}\ldots\omega_{n_k}^{i_ks_k},\;(i_1,\ldots,i_{k})\in\Gamma.
\end{eqnarray}
Consider two symmetric subsets $S_1,S_2$ in $\Gamma$. Observe that the eigenvector in Theorem \ref{c2} is independent of the connection set. Therefore the set of eigenvectors of both graphs $Cay(\Gamma, S_1 )$ and $Cay(\Gamma, S_2 )$, obtained by using Theorem \ref{c2}, are equal. Thus we have the following result.
\begin{prop}\label{3ab}
If $S_1$ and $S_2$ are symmetric subsets of an abelian group $\Gamma$ then adjacency matrices of the Cayley garphs $Cay(\Gamma, S_1 )$ and $Cay(\Gamma, S_2 )$ commute.
\end{prop}

In \cite{saxe}, the authors showed that a circulant graph, which is actually a Cayley graph over ${\mathbb Z}_n$, is periodic if and only if the graph is integral. Since periodicity is a necessary condition for PST in vertex transitive graph (see \cite{god2}), the result implies that if a circulant graph has PST then it must have integral spectrum. Now we generalize this for Cayley graphs.
