We illustrate Theorem \ref{6d} by the following example.
\begin{ex}\label{eg1}
Suppose $\Gamma={\mathbb Z}_4\oplus{\mathbb Z}_2\oplus{\mathbb Z}_3$ and let ${\mathbf D}=\left\lbrace(1,1,1),(1,2,1),(2,2,3),(4,1,3)\right\rbrace$. We show that the graph $Cay(\Gamma,S_{\Gamma}({\mathbf D}))$ admits PST at $\frac{\pi}{2}$. Let ${\mathbf D}_1=\left\lbrace(1,1,1),(1,2,1)\right\rbrace$. We already have in Example \ref{eg0} that ${\mathbf D}_1\in\mathscr{D}$. Now consider ${\mathbf D}_2=\left\lbrace(2,2,3),(4,1,3)\right\rbrace$. Here the connection set ${\mathbf C}$ in $X({\mathbf C})$ associated to $Cay(\Gamma,S_{\Gamma}({\mathbf D}_2))$ can be evaluated as ${\mathbf C}=\left\lbrace (0,1,0),(0,0,1)\right\rbrace.$ Thus we have ${\mathbf D}_2\in\tilde{\mathscr{D}}$. Note here that ${\mathbf D}$ generates $\Gamma$. Hence, by using Theorem \ref{6d}, we find that $Cay(\Gamma,S_{\Gamma}({\mathbf D}))$ is connected and exhibits PST at $\frac{\pi}{2}$.
\end{ex}

We have already seen that gcd-graphs over abelian groups of order odd do not exhibit PST. In the following theorem we find a necessary and sufficient condition for a class of gcd-graphs to be periodic at $\pi$. Here we add some more edges to a graph $Cay(\Gamma,S_{\Gamma}({\mathbf D}))$ admitting perfect PST at $\frac{\pi}{2^{k}},k\in{\mathbb N}$ and observe the behavior of the transition matrix. Using this, we will find some gcd-graphs not allowing PST at $\frac{\pi}{2^{k}},$ for all $k\in{\mathbb N}$. 

\begin{theorem}\label{6e}
Let $\Gamma$ be as defined in Lemma \ref{6b} and assume that $Cay(\Gamma,S_{\Gamma}({\mathbf D}))$ admits perfect state transfer at $\frac{\pi}{2^{k}},$ for some $k\in{\mathbb N}$. Suppose $d_{r+1},\ldots,d_{r+s}$ are fixed divisors of $p_{1}^{m_{1}},\ldots,p_{s}^{m_{s}}$, respectively. Consider ${\mathbf D}'=\left\lbrace {\mathbf d}=\left(d_1,\ldots,d_{r+1},\ldots,d_{r+s}\right)\in\Gamma\;:\;{\mathbf d} \text{ divides } {\mathbf m}_{\Gamma}\right\rbrace,$ so that ${\mathbf D}$ and ${\mathbf D}'$ are disjoint. Also suppose $Cay(\Gamma,S_{\Gamma}({\mathbf D}'))\cong X({\mathbf C}')\times G$ with $|{\mathbf C}'|\not\equiv 0\;(mod\;2)$. The graph $Cay(\Gamma,S_{\Gamma}({\mathbf D}\cup {\mathbf D}'))$ is periodic at $\pi$ if and only if the eigenvalues of the integral graph $G$ have same parity.
\end{theorem}
